SIMPLE: interdict
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interdict
<hw>In`ter*dict"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Interdicted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Interdicting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>entrediten</ets>
to forbid communion, L. <ets>interdicere</ets>, <ets>interdictum</ets>.
See <er>Interdict</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To forbid; to prohibit or debar; <as>as, to
<ex>interdict</ex> intercourse with foreign nations</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Charged not to touch the <qex>interdicted</qex> tree.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>To lay under an interdict; to cut
off from the enjoyment of religious privileges, as a city, a church, an
individual.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An archbishop may not only excommunicate and <qex>interdict</qex>
his suffragans, but his vicar general may do the same.</q>
<rj><qau>Ayliffe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interdict</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Interdict
<hw>In"ter*dict`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>entredit</ets>, <ets>enterdit</ets>, OF. <ets>entredit</ets>, F.
<ets>interdit</ets>, fr. L. <ets>interdictum</ets>, fr.
<ets>interdicere</ets> to interpose, prohibit; <ets>inter</ets> between
+ <ets>dicere</ets> to say. See <er>Diction</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A prohibitory order or decree; a
prohibition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These are not fruits forbidden; no <qex>interdict</qex>⟦br⟧
Defends the touching of these viands pure.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>A prohibition of the pope, by
which the clergy or laymen are restrained from performing, or from
attending, divine service, or from administering the offices or enjoying
the privileges of the church.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>An order of the court of
session, having the like purpose and effect with a writ of injunction
out of chancery in England and America.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interdiction</ent>⟦br⟧
